A table of contents can be generated automatically in a LATEX document using the `\tableofcontents` command. The `\tableofcontents` command takes a `\listofcontents` argument, which is a list of all the sections, subsections, and subsubsections in the document. The `\tableofcontents` command will then create a table of contents in the current page.

Here is an example of how a table of contents can be generated automatically in a LATEX document:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

\begin{document}

\title{My Document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
\subsection{Section A}
\subsubsection{Subsection A.1}
\section{Body}
\subsection{Section B}
\subsubsection{Subsection B.1}

\end{document}
```

The output of this code will be a table of contents that looks like this:

```
\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}

\subsection{Section A}

\subsubsection{Subsection A.1}

\section{Body}

\subsection{Section B}

\subsubsection{Subsection B.1}
```

As you can see, the `\tableofcontents` command has generated a table of contents that includes all the sections, subsections, and subsubsections in the document.

